==French==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|frm|fr}}, from {{m|frm|aborder}}, from {{etyl|fro|fr}} {{m|fro|aborder||to hit a ship in order to board it}}, from {{m|fro|bord||side of a ship, edge}}, from {{etyl|frk|fr}} {{m|frk|*bord||side of a ship or vessel}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|fr}} {{m|gem-pro|*burdą||edge, border, side}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|fr}} {{m|ine-pro|*bheredh-||to cut}}. Cognate with {{etyl|goh|-}} {{m|goh|bort||edge, rim, rand}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|bord||ship, side of a ship}}, {{etyl|non|-}} {{m|non|borð||edge, side of a vessel}}. More at {{l|en|board}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|Fr-abord.ogg|Audio|lang=fr}}

===Noun===
{{fr-noun|m}}

# {{label|fr|literary}} The [[manner]] with which one acts in the [[presence]] of another person or persons, especially in a first [[encounter]].
# {{label|fr|rare}} The [[surrounding]]s of a place.
# {{label|fr|archaic}} [[arrival|Arrival]] or [[accessibility]] by water.

====Usage notes====
* In the sense "surroundings", the word is almost always a [[pluralia tantum]].
* The sense "manner of acting" is usually now perceived as a backformation from {{m|fr|aborder||to approach}}, and is most common in the expression {{m|fr||être [[d'un abord]]}} and variations of it.

